            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Heather Miller\u2019s story began not under the fog of San Francisco, but in the relentless sun of the Central Valley. Raised in Modesto by a mechanic father and a mother who worked shifts at a grocery store, her childhood was defined by practicality and tight budgets. School was a place to get through, not excel in, and dreams of college felt like a foreign language. The future seemed a pre-written script of early marriage and a local service job, a life she watched her older brother embrace without question.\n\nHer turning point arrived at nineteen, on a weekend trip to San Francisco with a friend. The city\u2019s vibrant, chaotic energy was a revelation. It was the first place she felt anonymous and free simultaneously. Within a year, she had saved a few hundred dollars, packed a single suitcase, and moved into a cramped room in a shared Sunset District apartment. The first years were a blur of waitressing jobs and constant financial anxiety. Seeking stability, she enrolled in a short, intensive program to become a Certified Nursing Assistant (CNA), drawn to the profession\u2019s straightforward, caring mission.\n\nNow, at 38, Heather has built a life of quiet purpose. She works as a CNA for the San Francisco Unified School District, assigned to a student with severe cerebral palsy. Her days are physically and emotionally demanding, spent providing one-on-one care, assisting with mobility, and offering a steady, calming presence. Her $55,000 salary requires careful budgeting in a city of extremes.\n\nShe lives in the Inner Richmond, sharing a rent-controlled apartment with a roommate she met a decade ago. Her 2.5-mile commute on the 38-Geary bus is a daily ritual, a time to decompress with a podcast or simply watch the city wake up. Her social life is small but solid: weekly dinners with her roommate, occasional drinks with a few other school aides, and long walks through Golden Gate Park. She\u2019s had relationships, but her demanding job and financial constraints have made long-term partnership elusive.\n\nHeather\u2019s dreams are grounded. She aspires to save enough for a real vacation\u2014perhaps to Kauai\u2014and sometimes considers the daunting path of becoming a Licensed Vocational Nurse for better pay and security. More than anything, she cherishes the stability she\u2019s carved out for herself. She is a quiet, essential part of the city\u2019s complex heart\u2014the kind of person who makes San Francisco work, far from the headlines and tech campuses."
        },
